04814nam a22007575i 9780674056206DE-B159720210927121507.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210927t20102013mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979752463  a(OCoLC)999366749  a97806740562067 a10.4159/97806740562062doi  a(DE-B1597)457567  a(OCoLC)873806310  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aDS752.3b.B76 2010eb 7aHIS0080002bisacsh04a951/.0262221 aBrook, Timothy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Troubled Empire :bChina in the Yuan and Ming Dynasties /cTimothy Brook. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2010] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHistory of Imperial China ;v500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIintroduction -- t1. Dragon Spotting -- t2. Scale -- t3. The Nine Sloughs -- t4. Khan and Emperor -- t5. Economy and Ecology -- t6. Families -- t7. Beliefs -- t8. The Business of Things -- t9. The South China Sea -- t10. Collapse -- tConclusion -- tTemperature and Precipitation Extremes -- tThe Nine Sloughs -- tSuccession of Emperors -- tPronunciation Guide -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"The Mongol takeover in the 1270s changed the course of Chinese history. The Confucian empire—a millennium and a half in the making—was suddenly thrust under foreign occupation. What China had been before its reunification as the Yuan dynasty in 1279 was no longer what it would be in the future. Four centuries later, another wave of steppe invaders would replace the Ming dynasty with yet another foreign occupation. The Troubled Empire explores what happened to China between these two dramatic invasions. If anything defined the complex dynamics of this period, it was changes in the weather. Asia, like Europe, experienced a Little Ice Age, and as temperatures fell in the thirteenth century, Kublai Khan moved south into China. His Yuan dynasty collapsed in less than a century, but Mongol values lived on in Ming institutions. A second blast of cold in the 1630s, combined with drought, was more than the dynasty could stand, and the Ming fell to Manchu invaders. Against this background—the first coherent ecological history of China in this period—Timothy Brook explores the growth of autocracy, social complexity, and commercialization, paying special attention to China’s incorporation into the larger South China Sea economy. These changes not only shaped what China would become but contributed to the formation of the early modern world."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 0aCivilization, OrientalxHistory. 0aCommercexEnvironmental aspectszChinaxHistory. 0aCommercexSocial aspectszChinaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)z978311075606708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067405620640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674056206423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674056206/original  a978-3-11-044220-5  Harvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-075606-7  HUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)b2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGru